history.content: Well the kind of projects from 61b that you're mentioning are mostly thought of as "application-level" programming, whereas 162 is systems programming. In order to fill the "holes", I feel that you'd be better off either taking other coding-heavy classes or pursuing some side project on your own, as you have to keep in mind that 162 is an advanced upper-division course (that people, including proficient coders, are known to find challenging) and that if your fundamentals are weak, chances are that you'd find yourself struggling through 162 instead of making the most of it.

children.subject: 61B was just practice to get a better feel for data structures, their uses and their tradeoffs in the context of runtime and space complexity. If you wanted to practice those, I recommend coding practice websites like Leetcode more than I would 162, though 162 is a very important class in its own right, and should be one you take if you're into SWE.

history.content: I didn't try very hard in 61b (didn't do the bearmaps or help at all on the final project) and regret this as I feel like I have major holes in my SWE holes. Will taking and trying very hard in 162 fix these holes?
history.subject: Will 162 fix the SWE holes I have from 61b?
